Throughout Bolivia, which has no access to the sea, the memory of the lost coastline in favor of Chile during the resource conflict in the 19th century is still alive – just as much as the longing for re-seaways in the Pacific Ocean.
Bolivia is awaiting the judgment of the International Court of Justice on October 1, after a five-year trial, and hopes may be at their highest level in decades.
“Bolivia has a momentum, a spirit of unity and peace and, of course, is optimistic about the outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch the International Court of Justice's verdict on the big screen and hope that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia's position that Chile, after decades of demanding negotiations, is obliged to negotiate a sovereign sea exit to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president facing a controversial battle to be re-elected next year, may also benefit from Monday's verdict.
“We are on the cusp of returning the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia and that little would change if it did.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands has no authority to allocate Chilean territory and has said it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
