Morales's warlike rhetoric buried every goodwill in Chile, he said.
At some point, Bolivia and Chile will continue the dialogue, but after this, it will be extremely difficult to negotiate.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, the Bolivian representative in The Hague, disagrees with the view that the court ruled unusually quickly.
On Monday, it will bring Bolivia “an unprecedented opportunity to begin a new period in relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “break 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefit,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most favorite presidents – used the maritime issue as a political rodent.
