John Edward: The Language Skills Citizens of the World Need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam results, with additional weight given by individual and joint successes in sports, arts, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the above-mentioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be the preferred and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his native language, it goes to his heart."
This statement is a strong reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of the final exams this year show that the highest scores in languages were achieved by students of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who learned foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected in 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students received an excellent rating for Mandarin, while 72% of students learning German, 69% of students learning French and 63% of students learning Spanish also received the highest possible rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Today, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of workforce with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs require language knowledge, these skills are key in a globalised world.
Regardless of the choice of career, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such a long-term skill.
A person who speaks several languages can communicate directly with strangers, which gives him an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in 2013, 75% of respondents in the United Kingdom do not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to communicate on it, and French is the only language that speaks a two-digit percentage of respondents, namely 15%.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for children today.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classic, modern languages in their program, while others will opt for languages that are considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, independent schools will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are proficient in the field.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which they will learn to prepare and arm themselves with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future prepares us for.
The fact that in today’s global business world, language knowledge is very important for the future of every country, so it must also be reflected in education.
Thus, knowledge of modern languages should really be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer a choice of languages, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
