Harvard students take a class to learn how to get a good rest
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to get a good night's sleep in an attempt to fight the increasingly widespread culture of learning with caffeine and sleepless nights.
Academician found that students at the world's best university often have no idea about the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has devised a course he considers to be the first of its kind in the United States.
The idea for the course came after he gave a speech on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, "Why did I learn this only now, in my last year of college?"
She said no one told her how important the dream was, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help academic and sporting success and generally improve health.
A professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Paul Barreira Health Service says the University decided to introduce the course after students were spotted with a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a student bedroom where students have to click cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how lack of sleep affects success, and how important a sleep routine is.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
After that, a campus map with interactive icons is displayed that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know how cigarettes affect health,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in full-time learning before exams still exists, says the professor, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps in the fight against obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, throws it into a state of starvation and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler devise the course after attending his first year of Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As the next step, it plans to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar course of study before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking. They must be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
