Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert the right way to convince people to demand a call to action, or just another case of so-called “clickivism” – where people feel that by signing an online petition or sending a tweet they are really making a difference?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have recorded more than 19 million “actions” by its supporters who have striven to achieve a variety of goals.
It claims that these actions have been an incentive for world leaders to announce commitments and policies that will lead to more than $37 billion that will impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
