Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that aims to become a competitor to Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that is developing on the basis of Berners-Lee’s open platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and the people who will be allowed to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he said, thinking about the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "personal network storage" or POD.
It can contain contact lists, duty lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available on one browser at a time.
What is unique when it comes to personal online data storage is that it is the decision of who can access which information is completely user.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea for Inrupt, according to CEO John Bruce, is to provide the company with the resources, processes, and appropriate skills to help make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several engineers who signed a contract to work on the project, as well as a community of volunteer developers.
Starting this week, development engineers from around the world were able to build their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team were not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not they would introduce a complete change in which all of their business models overnight would be completely reversed.
“We don’t ask for their permission.”
In a press release, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts State Institute of Technology (MIT).
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even while launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the World Wide Web Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
“I am incredibly optimistic about the next era of the network,” Berners-Lee added.
