Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann won the prize on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglis and Lehaucourt.
However, four days later he was killed by a sniper and never learned that he had received the greatest British military honor.
A memorial stone was discovered by two of his grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "incredibly symbolic" that the stone would be discovered exactly 100 years after his grandfather's undertaking for which he received that recognition.
On 29 September 1918, Colonel Vann led his battalion across the St. Quentin Canal "through a very dense fog and under heavy fire coming from the battlefield and machine guns."
Later, he rushed to the front lines and with "incredible courage" led the unit forward before, without anyone's help, rushing to the Polish cannon and killing three of the military squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Vanna was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather’s works were “something I know I could never achieve, and that inspires humility.”
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid the wreath after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to be taking part in the parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is shown through the support that many people will give."
