The National Foundation is eavesdropping on the secret life of bats
New research on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape in hunting for food.
There is hope that the results will explain the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
A study conducted by scientists at the National Foundation for Scotland (NTS) will follow ordinary and swampy dwarf bats, as well as brown long-tailed and river bats in Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile scans using handheld detectors.
An expert analysis of the sound of all the recordings will determine the frequency of bat voting and what species does.
A habitat map and report will then be made to create a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS’s Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitats are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of working on habitat management, such as creating meadows and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are endangered by construction and decoration works that affect shelters and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as well as flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks of pet cats.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to find bugs and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct research, shelter inspections and sometimes rescue.
The organization even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of the ten species of bats that inhabit Scotland.
The manager, David Thompson, says the estate is the ideal area for them.
“Here in Threave we have a huge space for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all good habitats.
However, there’s a lot more we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other facilities will help us better understand what they need to progress.”
It stresses the importance of checking the presence of bats before starting maintenance work inside buildings, since the unintentional destruction of a single bed can kill up to 400 females and young, thus likely destroying the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture, harass or destroy their shelters.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a representative of the Scottish Flea Protection Association, urged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we simply don’t know how their population is progressing.”
