New data on red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Flora and Fauna (FWC) shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tide in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, heterogeneous algae bloom conditions are reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties <0xCC><0xB6> indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles along the coast from the northern part of Pinellas County to the southern part of Lee County.
Flowering areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, average concentrations have been recorded in the Collubal area in the Pinellas county or in the associated coastal area, low to high concentrations in the Hillsborough county coastal area, common to high concentrations in the Manatee county, common to high concentrations in the Sarasota county, or associated concentrations in the Sarasota county.
Respiratory irritation cases are still reported in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwest Florida during the past week.
